Counseling patients about therapy for localized prostate cancer.

Middleton RG(1).

Author information:
(1)Division of Urology, Health Sciences Center, University of Utah, Salt Lake 
City, USA.

The major therapeutic approaches to localized prostate cancer are radical 
prostatectomy, external beam radiation therapy, and surveillance or observation. 
The appropriate treatment for a specific patient depends on tumor stage, grade, 
and prostate-specific antigen (PSA) level, as well as on patient age, medical 
status, life expectancy, and patient preference. A patient with localized 
prostate cancer should understand the nature of these therapeutic approaches and 
their possible complications. In the absence of good long-term outcome data, 
patient preference is a significant factor.

